Flashcard Study Web App
Tutorial

Flashcard Study Web App

9 steps

We are now ready to build our own web app and deploy it to the internet for others to use. In this tutorial, we will be building a simple web app written in HTML, CSS and JavaScript. We will be learning the basics of how to initialise a project with Firebase and how to deploy our code to Firebase.

In this tutorial, we will be building a flashcard application to help students study. This web application will use local storage to store the data collected. After we are done with this web application, we will be deploying it to Firebase.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

HTML Intermediate
CSS Basics
JavaScript Basics

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:

  1. Initialize a firebase project with CLI
  2. Create a project with firebase using CLI
  3. Build a simple study application with raw HTML, CSS and JavaScript
  4. Deploy a web application to Firebase

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 9

  • Step 1: Setting Up Our Workspace

    We will now be creating a simple application called Study With Me. This application will allow users to create simple flashcards where they can hide or show the answers on each flashcard.

    Now, open the code editor of your choice. For this example, we will be using Visual Studio Code. We will create a new folder called StudyWithMe. We will store all of our files within this folder.

    Within the project root folder, lets create 2 new folders called css and js. Similar to other projects we have done in the past, these folders are where we can store our CSS and JavaScript files respectively.

    Once done, we will create 1 HTML file called index.html at the root directory. Next, create 2 new files, main.css and main.js and place them into the css folder and js folder respectively.

    Your directory should look like.

  • Step 2: Code Structure

    We will now be writing HTML code to be added into our index.html file. Add the following code to it.

    <!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Study With Me!</title>
  <script src="./js/main.js" defer></script>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="./css/main.css">
</head>
<body onload="loadBody()">
  <div class="header">
    <h1>Study with Me! by Stackie</h1>
</div>
 
  <div class="container">
    <div class="newCards">
      <h2>New Questions</h2>
      <div class="formInnerContainer">
        <label for="question">Question</label>
        <input id="questionField" type="text" name="question">
      </div>
 
      <div class="formInnerContainer">
        <label for="answer">Answer</label>
        <input id="answerField" type="text" name="answer">
      </div>
      <button id="submit" onclick="handleSubmit()" >Submit</button>
    </div>
 
    <div id="card-container"></div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
    HTML

    This HTML code is meant to structure the entire layout of the document. Within the <head> tag, we have also made reference to main.js and main.css. You may notice a keyword called defer within the <script> tag. This is to ensure that our HTML file will load all of the HTML elements before loading the script. This is to prevent any errors within our script from referencing any elements that have yet to be loaded.

    Lastly, similar to our other web application projects, we use the onload attribute in our <body> tag to invoke the function from our script. In this case, loadBody() will be run from our script.

    Our HTML structure will be split into 3 distinct sections. The header will be a simple title of our web application. The next section will be for users to input their questions and answers into the text field. The last section will be empty for now. This <div> will store all of the cards programmatically via JavaScript. Later on in our JavaScript, our code will retrieve all the information stored on the device and using recursion, it will append the cards into that <div> container.

  • Step 3: Styling Our Web App

    To style our web application, we will be adding the CSS rulesets below to the main.css file. 

    /* change font family to roboto */
 
body {
  font-family: 'Roboto', sans-serif;
}
 
.header{
  background-color:gray;
  padding: 10px;
  border-bottom: 1px solid #e5e5e5;
  color: white;
}
 
.cards-container{
  /* grid */
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(300px, 1fr));
  grid-gap: 20px;
  margin: 20px 0;
}
 
.card{
  background-color: #fff;
  border-radius: 5px;
  box-shadow: 0 2px 5px rgba(0,0,0,0.6);
  overflow: hidden;
  display: inline-grid;
  padding: 10px;
  margin: 10px;
  min-width: 30%;
}
 
.card h2{
  padding-bottom: 10px;
  border-bottom: 2px solid #e5e5e5;
  margin-top: 0px;
  font-size: 20px;
  margin-bottom: 0px;
}

  display: flex;

  justify-content: space-between;

  border: 2px dashed #e5e5e5;

  margin: 10px 0;
  padding: 10px;

  border-radius: 5px;

button{
  background-color: #e5e5e5;
  border: 1px solid #e5e5e5;
  border-radius: 5px;
  padding: 10px;
  margin: 10px 0;

  font-weight: bold;
  font-size: 20px;

    CSS

    These are simple styles applied to change the default native look of all components. Without styling, our web app will look unappealing to our users. Did you know, all browsers have their own native elements and components. Without styling, a default button may look different on a Safari-based Web App than a Chrome-based Web App.

    You may have noticed we have used display: flex; to arrange the various components. This method is a modern way to allow your elements to react dynamically to the other elements in its surroundings.

  • Step 4: Web App Initialisation

    You may have recalled in Step 2 that we used a onload attribute in our <body> tag to invoke the JavaScript function to load all the cards on to the document. Insert the following code into your main.js file.

    function loadBody () {
  let currentCards = localStorage.getItem("cards")
  if (currentCards == null) {
    currentCards = []
  }else{
    currentCards = JSON.parse(currentCards)
  }
 
  let htmlText = ""
  for (let i = 0; i < currentCards.length; i++) {
    htmlText += 
    `<div class="card" onclick="handleState(${i})">
      <h2>${currentCards[i].question}</h2>
      <div id="card-${i}">
        <p>${currentCards[i].answer}</p>
        <button onclick="handleDelete(${i})">Remove</button>
      </div>
    </div>`
  }
 
  document.getElementById("card-container").innerHTML = htmlText
}
    JavaScript

    This is the function that is responsible for loading the data from the localStorage and displaying it in the document. We use localStorage.getItem() to retrieve data from the localStorage. Browser storage can only store string data. However, we are dealing with arrays and objects for our web application. Using JSON.parse(), we can convert the string data from localStorage back to a readable Object for us to use in JavaScript.

    You may notice that within the for loop, the function will loop through an array to display the cards. You may also notice the use of some HTML code here as it is used as the template of each card.

    Using string formatting, we are able to change the id and innerText of the HTML dynamically. We are also invoking functions like handleState() and handlerDelete() which we can use to hide and show the answers, as well as to delete the cards. What is interesting is that we can put in an argument, which is the current iterable variable for the function to make reference to the card stored in local storage.

  • Step 5: Create, Hide and Delete

    We will now be adding the final functions needed for our web application to work. Append the code below into your main.js file. 

    function handleSubmit() {
  let question = document.getElementById("questionField").value;
  let answer = document.getElementById("answerField").value;
  var currentCards = localStorage.getItem("cards")
  if (question && answer){
    if (currentCards == null) {
      currentCards = []
    } else{
      currentCards = JSON.parse(currentCards)
    }
    currentCards.push({question: question, answer: answer})
    localStorage.setItem("cards", JSON.stringify(currentCards))
    document.getElementById("questionField").value = ""
    document.getElementById("answerField").value = ""
    loadBody()
  }
}
 
function handleState (index) {
  let card = document.getElementById(`card-${index}`)
  if (card.style.display == "none") {
    card.style.display = "block"
  }else{
    card.style.display = "none"
  }
}
 
function handleDelete (index) {
  let currentCards = localStorage.getItem("cards")
  if (currentCards == null) {
    currentCards = []
  }else{
    currentCards = JSON.parse(currentCards)
  }
  currentCards.splice(index, 1)
  localStorage.setItem("cards", JSON.stringify(currentCards))
  loadBody()
}
    JavaScript

    These 3 functions have been invoked in the previous steps above. For example, in handleSubmit(), this function has been called from the main document. This function will take in the raw values of the question and answer by referencing their element id from the document. It will retrieve the current data from localStorage and append the new data to the current data. From there, it will convert the data to a string using JSON.stringify() as localStorage only stores data in string format.

    The handleState() will take in 1 parameter which is the index of the card. From there, we will toggle the visibility of answers to ensure that the cards can be shown or hidden on demand.

    Lastly, the handleDelete() will also take in the index number of the question. It will retrieve from the existing localStorage and remove the card data from the overall object. After doing so, it will store the final data back into the localStorage.

  • Step 6: Project Initialisation

    Before we can upload our code to Firebase, we will need to tell Firebase that this project is a Firebase project.

    In our root directory, create a new folder called build. All the code we would like Firebase to look for will be within the build folder. We will now copy all the contents within the root folder into the build folder. Your studywithme directory should look like this:

    Now, within your code editor, open up the terminal and enter the following code:

    firebase login

    This will redirect us to our web browser. We will need to log in to our Google Account on the web browser. Behind the scenes, Google is trying to authenticate your account to grant access to your terminal. Upon a successful login, you may return to your code editor. You should be able to see a success message and your Gmail account.

    Return to your Firebase console. Click on 'Add project'. Give your project a name. In our case, it would be username-studywithme. Replace username with your own StackUp name.

    On naming your project id: It must be 6 to 30 lowercase letters, digits or hyphens. It must start with a letter. In the event that the project name already exists, you should do your best to make the name unique by adding numbers to the end of your project name.

    Next, you will be asked if you want to enable Google Analytics for your Firebase project. This is optional for us now as we do not need to track site metrics. Proceed to create your project.

    Back to your terminal, we will need to initialize this project to our Firebase account. Enter the following command to do so. 

    firebase init

    You should be able to see this. We need to select the Hosting: Configure files for Firebase Hosting and (optionally) set up GitHub Action deploys We will need to use our arrow keys on our keyboard to interact with the CLI. Next, press the spacebar on your keyboard to select and ENTER/RETURN to continue. 

    Next, move your arrow keys to the row Use an existing project. Press Enter/Return to confirm your selection. Select the name of the project you created earlier on Firebase console.

    Troubleshooting: In the event that you receive an error, do check your firebase-debug.log. Look out for the error code, such as HTTP Error: 403. Use this information to ask for help on the Discord server. In the event your log says "HTTP Error: 403, The caller does not have permission", you may want to check if you are logged in on your terminal. A suggested method is to use the commands: firebase logout and then firebase login.

    When asked 'What do you want to use as your public directory?', you will notice (public) is given. Enter 'build' since this is the folder which contains the files that you want to deploy to the web. Press Enter.

    Important: Now Firebase is asking if you want them to rewrite all files into a single file. Press N on your keyboard. If we press Y, it will simply overwrite all the code that we have in the index.html file, and that will lead to our page not deploying later on.

    You may choose to 'set up automatic builds and deploys with GitHub', which will upload your code here to GitHub as well. For this tutorial, we will not need to do so, as such, select N.

    Next, 'File build/index.html already exists. Overwrite?' Select N for this as we want to retain the current index.html file that we have written.

    Congratulations, we have completed setting up our project on Firebase. We may now move on to deploying our code.

  • Step 7: Code Deployment

    We are nearing the final step to deploy our code to the Internet. Lets recap. Every project will require a Firebase initialisation. This is to allow Firebase to write configuration files in our project directory for them to upload the code seamlessly. Using firebase init we initialised the project. We placed all of our source code within the build folder as Firebase will read all the files within build and upload it to the cloud.

    We strongly recommend you to develop your code at the root directory and copy them to the build folder. This is to prevent Firebase from overwriting any files you have created. If they overwrite any files, you will still be able to keep the original file.

    Now after knowing how Firebase works in the backend, we are ready to deploy. Simply open up your terminal within your code editor and type in the following command.

    firebase deploy

    And thats it. We have deployed the code into the internet. Firebase will also return the default link to access the project and you may use that hosting URL to share with others.

    In the event you need to make any changes to your website. Simply ensure that the updated files are placed in the build folder and run the firebase deploy command.

  • Step 8: Checking Your Work

    Great job following till the end! Time to check if you have done everything correctly. 

    Head to your hosting URL, the one with the web.app domain. You should see an interface like this.

    Create a question and answer, then press Submit. Your flashcard should appear below, with only the question shown. Upon clicking the flashcard, the answer is shown. Click the Remove button, and the flashcard should disappear.

    Congratulations, your Flashcard Web App works just as intended.

  • Step 9: Troubleshooting

    Having problems viewing your web app? Some users have reported the following issues.

    When I run firebase deploy, I get HTTP Error: 404, Requested entity was not found

    In this case, Stack Overflow has two possible solutions - here and here.

    My web.app URL shows "Firebase Hosting Setup Complete". Where is the page I worked on?

    During deployment, there is a chance that you configured your project as a single-page app. To determine if this is true, open your index.html file in your build folder. If the code inside is not what you worked on, you need to replace the code. The solution then would be to replace all the files in the build folder and run firebase deploy again.

    I received the error: An unexpected error has occurred.

    In your directory, remove the firebase.json and .firebaserc files. Close your terminal, and reopen it. Then attempt to deploy again. For more details, it is best to check your error log.

    When I visit my hosting URL, I see a page that says "404 Page Not Found".

    When asked to indicate your public directory, you did not indicate the build folder. As a result, the files in your build folder were not deployed to Firebase. Start from the beginning by running firebase init and ensure that you follow the instructions carefully.
